docs.snippet: Many digital currency issues, known as initial coin offerings (ICOs), will be treated as securities under regulatory guidelines published on Friday by Switzerland, which has become a global leader in the hot fundraising method.

headline.main: Swiss Watchdog to Treat Some Cryptocurrency Offerings as Securities
headline.print_headline: Swiss Watchdog to Treat Some Cryptocurrency Offerings as Securities

docs.snippet: Venezuela's new "petro" cryptocurrency will attract investments from Turkey, Qatar, the United States and Europe, the country's cryptocurrency regulator said on Friday.

headline.main: Venezuela Cryptocurrency to Draw Investment From Turkey, Qatar-Official
headline.print_headline: Venezuela Cryptocurrency to Draw Investment From Turkey, Qatar-Official

docs.snippet: Less than 100 people out of the 250,000 individuals who have already filed federal taxes this year through company Credit Karma reported a cryptocurrency transaction to U.S. tax authorities, the company said on Tuesday.

headline.main: Few Americans Reporting Cryptocurrency Trading to IRS for Now: Report
headline.print_headline: Few Americans Reporting Cryptocurrency Trading to IRS for Now: Report

docs.snippet: A group of cryptocurrency traders will file a lawsuit against Coincheck Inc on Thursday over last month's theft of $530 million in digital money from the Tokyo-based exchange, a lawyer representing the claimants said.

headline.main: Cryptocurrency Traders to Launch Lawsuit Against Coincheck on Thursday: Lawyer
headline.print_headline: Cryptocurrency Traders to Launch Lawsuit Against Coincheck on Thursday: Lawyer

docs.snippet: A group of academics and technology experts will soon launch a blockchain-powered network that will reward quality research with its own cryptocurrency called Mosaic.

headline.main: Mosaic Network Will Reward Researchers With Its Own Cryptocurrency

docs.snippet: The U.S. derivatives regulator warned investors on Thursday about cryptocurrency "pump-and-dump" scams that aim to rip off investors by inflating the price of volatile virtual tokens through spreading bogus information.

headline.main: U.S. Regulator Warns of Cryptocurrency 'Pump-And-Dump' Schemes

docs.snippet: Bank of Japan Governor Haruhiko Kuroda said on Tuesday cryptocurrencies likely won't threaten legal tenders like the yen any time soon as they are mostly used for speculative trading, rather than as payments and settlement means.

headline.main: BOJ Kuroda Says Cryptocurrency Won't Threaten Yen, Largely Speculative
headline.print_headline: BOJ Kuroda Says Cryptocurrency Won't Threaten Yen, Largely Speculative

docs.snippet: After the Mt. Gox cryptocurrency exchange was stung by a half-billion dollar theft in 2014, Japanese regulators swung into action.

docs.snippet: Cryptocurrency investors launched a lawsuit against Coincheck Inc on Thursday, seeking to force the Tokyo-based exchange to allow them to withdraw assets worth $183,000 frozen after last month's $530 million heist of digital money.

headline.main: Coincheck Hit by Lawsuit as Investors Seek Restart of Cryptocurrency Withdrawals
headline.print_headline: Coincheck Hit by Lawsuit as Investors Seek Restart of Cryptocurrency Withdrawals
